tion Security"}]	{Negotiation,Problem-solving,Communication,Leadership,"Crisis Management"}	f
db12dcae-8241-4e4d-8b98-d4867ac17d55	Ï∂úÍ∑º-ÎßâÎßâÌïú-dev-2026-01-02T09-08-06	en	First Day, Daunted by Dev Environment Setup: How Should I Ask the Team Lead?	This is the story of an intern's first day at work in Software Development Team 2, R&D Division, at 'Hansung Precision,' a domestic mid-sized automotive parts manufacturer. Hansung Precision is currently accelerating its smart factory transformation and undertaking an upgrade project for its existing Manufacturing Execution System (MES). This morning, you received your first task from Team Lead Park Jun-ho, the practical head of the team, to set up the development environment for the 'HS-MES 2.0' system. However, the provided guide document was written three years ago and contains many discrepancies with the current system environment, halting progress for over 30 minutes. All team members are engrossed in their individual tasks, making the office quiet enough to only hear keyboard sounds, and you feel an overwhelming pressure, unsure of who to approach. This scenario is designed to train communication skills for effectively overcoming the initial technical and relational barriers a new employee faces in an unfamiliar environment.\n\nThe core cause of the problem lies in information asymmetry and tacit knowledge within the organization. As an intern, you have no information regarding the project's history, system change logs, or the team's communication culture. In contrast, the team lead and other team members inherently share this context. The outdated document not being updated isn't a clear mistake by someone, but rather because busy practitioners didn't feel the need to document content they were already familiar with. Therefore, you face the challenge of systematically organizing and conveying not just that 'it's not working,' but also what you have attempted with your limited information, where you got stuck, and what specific information you need to resolve the issue.\n\nThe conflict in this situation exists between 'an intern desperately needing help but bearing the weight of asking a question' and 'a team lead with limited time but a responsibility to foster team members' growth.' Knowing that first impressions are crucial, you fear appearing incompetent or passive. Simultaneously, you worry about unnecessarily taking up your busy superior's time. Team Lead Park Jun-ho is extremely busy due to an impending project deadline and values efficiency above all else. He doesn't discourage questions per se, but he strongly dislikes inefficient communication that takes a long time to grasp the core of the problem. Therefore, resolving the conflict depends on building a bridge of communication based on mutual respect and efficiency, even before finding a technical solution.\n\nIf you fail to communicate effectively in this situation, in the short term, you will not be able to complete the development environment setup today, leading to a delay in your first task. This could decrease your confidence and become the start of a vicious cycle where you hesitate even more to ask questions when encountering similar problems in the future. In the long term, there's a risk of solidifying a negative first impression as a 'new hire who cannot solve problems independently' or a 'new hire who fails to grasp the essence of a question.' This could make the team lead hesitant to delegate tasks to you and limit your growth opportunities. For the team as a whole, it leads to inefficiency by delaying the early empowerment of new personnel.\n\nAs a new intern in the R&D Division, you should use this simulation to acknowledge your technical limitations and learn how to effectively utilize organizational resources to overcome them. The expected role is not just a questioner, but a 'well-prepared questioner.' You must master a three-step approach: objectively analyzing your situation (understanding the phenomenon), explaining the efforts you have made (problem-solving attempts), and clearly stating what you need from the other person (specific requests). Through this experience, it is crucial to realize that communication at work is not about exposing 'what you don't know,' but rather a collaborative process of aligning information 'to solve problems together.'	Today is your first day at work, 10:30 AM. Your department is Software Development Team 2, R&D Division, a key growth engine for 'Hansung Precision'. The team is currently facing the release of a Q3 system stabilization patch, creating a heightened sense of tension, and the office is unusually quiet. This morning, you received a PDF file titled 'HS-MES 2.0 Development Environment Setup Guide' from Team Lead Park Jun-ho and took your seat. However, the document was written based on a 3-year-old version (v1.5), so the currently used library versions or internal server IP addresses do not match. You have attempted to follow the guide for over 30 minutes, but are repeatedly encountering the error message: 'DB Connection Failed: Unknown host'. You searched for related documents on Confluence, the internal collaboration tool, but could not find an updated version. All colleagues around you are focused on their monitors, making it difficult to approach them. In particular, Team Lead Park Jun-ho is intently staring at his monitor and rapidly drafting a document, causing you extreme anxiety and pressure that your question might interrupt his critical workflow. Checking his schedule, a crucial video conference with an external vendor is set for 11 AM, making this an urgent situation where you might have to wait until the afternoon if you don't speak to him now.	Intern / Software Development Team 2, R&D Division / New Hire (no prior work experience) / To adapt to the team's development process and learn tasks through assigned projects. Specifically, to learn how to clearly communicate situations and request help when problems arise.	t	f	\N	2026-01-21 04:13:00.266027	2026-01-21 04:13:08.178	First day at work, morning. The team lead has back-to-back meetings scheduled starting at 11 AM. The implicit goal is to complete the development environment setup and successfully perform a basic build today.	Through this conversation, you can achieve a smooth start to work and a positive first impression, but failure risks branding you as an incompetent and inefficient new hire. In the short term, you will waste over half a day, and in the long term, it could lead to decreased confidence and a fear of asking questions. From Team Lead Park Jun-ho's perspective, 5 minutes of clear communication could rapidly accelerate a team member's growth, but 30 minutes of unclear dialogue could cost him critical work time. This directly impacts the team's overall productivity. Quantitatively, an intern's unproductive time and a leader's opportunity cost are at stake; qualitatively, it concerns team trust-building, the psychological stability of a new team member, and the crucial first step towards an efficient collaborative culture.	{"Clearly define the current situation and problem: Instead of vague phrases like 'the development environment isn't setting up,' you must be able to explain, based on specific facts, which document you followed, which steps you took, and exactly what error message occurred. This is to minimize the time it takes for the other person to understand the problem and propose a solution.","Demonstrate efforts made: Before asking for help, you must specifically show what attempts you made to solve the problem yourself (e.g., searching internal documents, analyzing error messages). This is a process of gaining trust by proving your proactive willingness to solve problems, rather than passively waiting for help.","Convey clear and specific requests: You must clearly state what you want from the team lead. Instead of simply saying 'Please help me,' you should clarify the goal of the conversation through actionable, specific requests such as 'Are there any updated documents?' or 'Could you briefly look at my screen with me?'","Learn efficient communication methods and build relationships: Through this conversation, you should identify the team lead's preferred communication style and problem reporting system, and establish guidelines for how to act in similar situations in the future. This is the first step towards successfully adapting to the team and building positive collaborative relationships, beyond mere problem-solving."}	Clearly communicates the current situation, attempts made, error encountered, and their thoughts. Team Lead Park Jun-ho immediately grasps the problem, provides a link to an updated document, and gives positive feedback like, 'It's good that you organized your question like this. Please continue to do so.' The conversation concludes within 5 minutes, and you return to your seat with a clear solution.	The overall message is conveyed, but with some minor gaps in explanation, leading the team lead to ask one or two additional questions (e.g., 'Did you check the error logs?'). After you answer his questions smoothly, he provides a direction for resolution, and you solve the problem independently based on his hints. There was some tension, but you successfully resolved the problem and gained confidence.	Due to anxiety, your explanation is somewhat verbose and disorganized, leading the team lead to interrupt several times, asking for the core issue (e.g., 'So, what exactly is the problem?' 'What are you requesting?'). Eventually, through his guided questions, the situation is barely understood, and he provides a solution with a slight sigh. The problem is resolved, but it leaves you feeling somewhat intimidated and hesitant to ask future questions.	You fail to properly explain the problem, repeating vague statements like 'It just doesn't work well.' You also fumble when trying to organize your attempts to solve it. Ultimately, Team Lead Park Jun-ho stops the conversation, saying, 'Please go back to your seat, write down 