 Park Su-jin (ISFJ) is extremely concerned about the negative impact of team discord on the project schedule, focusing solely on resolving the conflict and resuming development. Upon hearing the news, CTO Lee Yu-jin (INFJ) recognizes this incident as a serious issue that goes beyond mere project delay, potentially undermining the company's healthy debate culture and stunting the team's long-term growth potential.\n\nIf this conflict is not resolved quickly, development of the 'real-time synchronization' feature will be completely halted, leading to an indefinite postponement of the 'SynergyFlow 2.0' release. This could result in projected revenue losses amounting to hundreds of millions of Korean Won and the worst outcome of ceding market leadership to competitors. Furthermore, if a key member like Senior Developer Kim Cheol-min departs, securing a replacement and managing the handover will incur significant time and cost. A culture of distrust and blame could take root within the team, greatly increasing the risk of passive and defensive attitudes prevailing in all future collaborative processes.\n\nAs the 3-year experienced developer at the center of this issue, you are now responsible for proactively resolving this complex interpersonal and conflict situation, beyond merely performing technical tasks. Your goal is not just to mend strained relationships, but to transform this crisis into an opportunity for the team to grow to the next level. To achieve this, you must identify the hidden needs and emotions of each stakeholder and propose a reasonable solution acceptable to all, through logical reasoning and sincere communication. This task will be a crucial test, demonstrating not only your technical competence but also your conflict resolution skills, communication abilities, and commitment to contributing to the organization.	The argument that began during yesterday's code review session has left a deep wound across the entire development team. Since walking out of the meeting room, Senior Developer Kim Cheol-min has not responded to any of your messages on Slack channels, and this morning he has been pointedly ignoring you, avoiding eye contact. A heavy silence hangs over his desk, and even nearby colleagues are hesitant to speak, sensing the tension. PM Park Su-jin is displaying extreme anxiety, visiting your and Senior Developer Kim Cheol-min's desks alternately every hour, urging, 'We must resolve this today, no matter what.' She has already begun drafting a schedule delay report, preparing for the worst-case scenario. To make matters worse, you received a message from CTO Lee Yu-jin stating, 'If the two of you cannot find a breakthrough to resolve this issue by 5 PM today, I will have no choice but to intervene personally.' This is not merely an offer of mediation but effectively a warning that this is your last chance to autonomously resolve the situation. Rumors are starting to circulate within the team, portraying you as 'the junior who disrespected a senior' or Kim Cheol-min as 'the old-fashioned senior who resists change,' escalating the political pressure on both of you. If you do not act immediately, this conflict could escalate beyond a personal issue, leading to the imminent collapse of the entire team.	Developer / Development Team / 3rd-year experienced / As one of the responsible developers for critical feature development, you have the technical responsibility to ensure code quality. Concurrently, as a direct party to this conflict, you bear the significant responsibility of restoring your relationship with the senior developer and normalizing teamwork to successfully complete the project.	t	f	\N	2026-01-21 07:25:32.896519	2026-01-21 07:25:32.896519	There are exactly 14 days left until the launch of the new product, 'SynergyFlow 2.0'. The 'real-time synchronization' feature in question must complete its Code Freeze by this Friday and be handed over to the QA team by Monday morning next week. A single day's